<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="56" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[107,222,392,410]" box="[107,222,392,410]" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[107,222,392,410]" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[106,1096,430,577]" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">
The external genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KERTESZ ER" authorityYear="1903" box="[365,594,431,454]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernyi">
<emphasis box="[365,594,431,454]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Heteromeringia czernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="WILLISTON ILLIST" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[891,997,430,454]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[891,997,430,454]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 36-38" captionStartId="35.[732,769,772,794]" captionTargetBox="[110,701,174,904]" captionTargetId="figure-117@35.[106,711,170,911]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="Figs 36-38: Heteromeringia flavifrons HENNIG, genitalia. 36 internal, left lateral; 37 external, left lateral; 38 external, posterior. Phallapodeme missing from dissected specimen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752014" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752014/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Figs 36- 38</figureCitation>
), but the distiphallus, in which both ribs end in separate fringes, resembles that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="HENNIG" authorityYear="1938" box="[972,1096,461,485]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">
<emphasis box="[972,1096,461,485]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. flavifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[115,189,491,515]" captionStart="Figs 39-41" captionStartId="35.[730,767,1511,1533]" captionTargetBox="[117,694,943,1645]" captionTargetId="figure-153@35.[106,711,934,1654]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="Figs 39-41: Heteromeringia flavipes ((WIL WILLISTON), genitalia. 39 external, left lateral; 40 right surstylus, dorsal; 41 internal genitalia, left lateral. Ejaculatory apodeme omitted." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752018" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752018/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
). The phalli of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lonsdale &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2007" box="[344,479,491,515]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadriseta">
<emphasis box="[344,479,491,515]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. quadriseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lonsdale &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2007" box="[529,648,492,510]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="medianamediana">
<emphasis box="[529,648,492,510]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. medianamediana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[660,735,491,515]" captionStart="Figs 42-44" captionStartId="36.[190,227,711,733]" captionTargetBox="[390,981,181,685]" captionTargetId="figure-139@36.[381,986,174,690]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Figs 42-44: Heteromeringia mediana sp. n., genitalia. 42 internal, left lateral; 43 external, left lateral; 44 external, posterior. Ejaculatory apodeme omitted." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752022" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752022/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Figs 42</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[785,813,491,515]" captionStart="Figs 45-47" captionStartId="36.[190,227,1378,1400]" captionTargetBox="[386,983,908,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-103@36.[382,987,897,1364]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Figs 45-47: Heteromeringia quadriseta sp. n., genitalia. 45 internal, left lateral; 46 external, left lateral; 47 external, posterior. Ejaculatory apodeme omitted." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752026" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752026/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">45</figureCitation>
) also end in fringes, but the ends of the ribs are fused; furthermore, the ribs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lonsdale &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2007" box="[611,746,522,546]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrisetaquadriseta">
<emphasis box="[611,746,522,546]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. quadrisetaquadriseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are poorly defined and the phallus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lonsdale &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2007" box="[134,253,553,571]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediana">
<emphasis box="[134,253,553,571]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. mediana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is interrupted medially, creating basal and distal sections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[106,1096,591,737]" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName authorityName="K ERTESZ" authorityYear="1903" box="[106,338,591,615]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernyiczernyi">
<emphasis box="[106,338,591,615]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Heteromeringia czernyiczernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MELANDERMELANDER &amp; ARGO" authorityYear="1924" box="[396,541,591,615]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumipennis">
<emphasis box="[396,541,591,615]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. fumipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the most commonly collected 
<emphasis box="[913,1066,592,615]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">HeteromeringiaHeteromeringia</emphasis>
in Central and South America. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KERTESZ ER" authorityYear="1903" box="[409,640,622,645]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernyi">
<emphasis box="[409,640,622,645]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Heteromeringia czernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively easy to identify, being the only member of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KERTESZ ER" authorityYear="1903" box="[262,363,653,676]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernyi">
<emphasis box="[262,363,653,676]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">H. czernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group with three fronto-orbitals, a brown thorax and brown fore tarsi. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MELANDERMELANDER &amp; ARGO" authorityYear="1924" box="[162,429,683,707]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Heteromeringia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumipennis">
<emphasis box="[162,429,683,707]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="56">Heteromeringia fumipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is significantly larger and darker, the wing is darkly clouded, all of the genal bristles are poorly developed and the male has an anepisternal disc.
</paragraph>
